With the advent of ChatGPT, "AI" has become the ultimate buzz word. Now, <em>I, Robot, Her,</em> and <em>Terminator</em> seem like more than just lovable sci-fi classics -- they seem like plausible near futures.

A key component of many of the AI models we see today are <em>neural-networks</em>: computer systems modeled (roughly) on the human brain that allow computers to "learn". As someone interested in researching AI and its applications, I've always wanted to deep-dive into the specifics of how these networks work.

Now, I know how they work at high level (feed forward step, backpropogation step, need for MLP for XOR problem, activation functions to introduce non-linearity, CNNs for translation independence, e.t.c.) and can even train my own models. However, I've always felt that I don't really know something until I've built it or spent hours playing around with it.

As such, <em>I've set out to build a neural network from the ground up, using minimal libraries, in C++</em>. I already kinda tried to do this a few months back using 3B1B's video as a guide, but things didn't go that well...let's just say it's not a good idea to build all the functions for your neural network before testing any of them.

