<h2>I. Linear Regression with 1-D Inputs & Outputs</h2>

I'll be starting off by building a simple linear regression model. A throwback to elementary school, linear models are of the form:

$$
f(x) = wx + b
$$

<em>Linear regression</em> involves finding a <em>linear</em> function that accurately maps inputs to outputs (ex: apartment square feet ($x$) and rent ($y$)). In layman's terms, it's the process of finding the "best fit line" for some data points in the form ($x$, $y$). In this case, we're tweaking $w$ and $b$ to make $f(x)$ spit out a value close to $y$ for a given $x$. There are more complex forms of linear regression we'll get into later, but we're gonna start with this. To build this linear regression model, I'll:

<ol>
  <li>Create some data to test the model with (simple linear line)</li>
  <li>Write a "loss function" that allows me to quantify the effectiveness of the current model in fitting said data</li>
  <li>Write a "train" method which gradually adjusts the parameters of the linear function to make it more accurate</li>
</ol>

Creating the data is pretty straightforward. I know the linear function I'm wanting my model to "find" is gonna be $y = 3x + 1$, so I just created ordered pairs that follow this function:

```js
///*main.cpp*///

int main(int argc, const char * argv[]) {
    vector<double> x;
    vector<double> y;

    // Fill x with values from 0 to 5
    for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i) {
        x.push_back(i);
    }

    // Fill y with a roughly linear relationship to x (y = 3x + 1)
    for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i) {
        y.push_back(3 * x[i] + 1);
    }
}
```

