Now things get a little more dicey. Priming things for the future, I went ahead and set up a NeuralNet class (yay OOP). In it, I've got the function signature for a constructor (to set the learning rate for our model), our loss function (MSE), and the a train function (to find optimum values of $w$ and $b$).

```js
///*NeuralNet.h*///

class NeuralNet {
    public:
        NeuralNet(double learningRate);
        static double MSE(vector<double> &experimental, vector<double> &expected);
        void train(vector<double> input, vector<double> actualOutput, int epochs);

    private:
        double learningRate;
};
```

We'll be using <em>mean squared error</em> as our <strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loss_function">loss function</a></strong>, which helps quantify the accuracy of our current model. The formula for this is as follows:
$$
MSE =
\frac{1}{n}
\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^n(f(x_i) - y_i)^2
$$
<figcaption align="center">Mean Squared Error Function</figcaption>

In this case, $n$ represents the number of examples in our training data set, and $x_i$ and $y_i$ represent a single input-output pair. Indicated by the word "error" in the name here, we want the value of our loss function to be low!

MSE finds the average amount by which my function $f(x)$ is "off" at predicting a $y$ value given a particular $x$ value. We square the difference between $f$ and $y$ to 1) allow our average to work as expected with negative numbers and 2) keep our cost function as a differentiable function, which will come in handy later. Here's the function definition for this:

```js
double NeuralNet::MSE(vector<double> &calculated, vector<double> &truthy)
{
    double sum = 0;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < calculated.size(); ++i)
    {
        sum += pow(calculated[i] - truthy[i], 2);
    }
    return sum / (double)calculated.size();
}
```

Now comes the training function. With this, I'm trying to find the $w$ and $b$ values which minimize the MSE cost function above. Rewriting the MSE function with $w$ and $b$ in it (and replacing MSE with $J$ for notational simplicity), we have the following function:

$$
MSE = J(w, b) =
\frac{1}{n}
\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^n(wx_i+b - y_i)^2
$$

Now, at this point, things might feel a bit like alphabet soup with all the formulas, so let's try and visualize what's going on here. Given a fixed set of training points ($(x, y)$ pairs), if we graph $J(w, b)$, $w$ and $b$ in a 3-D plane, we get the following <a href="https://gist.github.com/JackTNorris/89c02f43f61b52b27e7843fcad061218">soup-bowl looking graph</a>:

