</p>

<figcaption align="center">Graph of Our Loss Function</figcaption>

With our train function, we want to select a $w$ and a $b$ that minimizes our cost function $J$. We can see where this is graphically (at the bottom of our "soup bowl"), but how do we get there programatically? If we've selected a $w$ and $b$, how do we know how to tweak them in order to minimize our cost function? The answer (in this case) is an optimization method called <strong><a href="https://www.ibm.com/topics/gradient-descent">gradient descent</a></strong>.

For starters, we've got to calculate the partial derivatives of $J$ with respect to $w$ and $b$, $\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{w}}$ and $\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{b}}$:

$$
\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{w}} = \frac{2}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(wx_i+b - y_i)x_i
$$
$$
\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{b}} = \frac{2}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(wx_i+b - y_i)
$$

By doing this, we've effectively calculated the <em>gradient</em> of the function $J(w,b)$:

$$
\nabla{
J(w, b) = \begin{bmatrix}
\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{w}} \ \\
\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{b}}
\end{bmatrix} =
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{2}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(wx_i+b - y_i)x_i \ \\
\frac{2}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(wx_i+b - y_i)
\end{bmatrix}

}
$$

If you're unfamiliar with the idea of a gradient -- don't worry. The main thing to know here is that this gradient tells us the the rate of change of $J$ with respect to its independent variables at a given point. If you plot this gradient as a vector at said point, it points in the direction of steepest ascent, with the magnitude of this vector growing as the ascent grows steeper.

Given that our gradient vector indicates the direction of <em>steepest</em> ascent, we want to "nudge" our weights & biases in the <em>opposite</em> direction of the gradient. Based on this, we have the following formula, in which $\alpha$ represents our <strong>learning rate</strong>:

$$
w_{new} = w_{old} - \alpha\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{w}}
$$
$$
b_{new} = b_{old} - \alpha\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{b}}
$$

The "learning rate" dictates the rate at which we find the optimal values of $w$ and $b$. I'll commentate on this a bit more in the future, but the thing to know with it for now is that you don't want it to be too big (or else $J$ will never converge to its lowest value, "ping-ponging" between solutions that are too high and too low) or too small (or else $J$ will take forever to converge on its lowest value).

With our train function, we'll iteratively adjust our weight and bias using the formula above. An <strong>epoch</strong>, as mentioned in the function below, represents a single one of these iterations. The code for this train function is listed below:

```js
/* NeuralNet.cpp */
void NeuralNet::train(vector<double> inputs, vector<double> expectedOutputs, int epochs)
{
    srand(time(NULL));
    double weight = random() % 40;
    double bias = random() % 40;
    for(int epoch = 0; epoch < epochs; epoch++)
    {
        vector<double> my_calc;
        double temp_weight_update = 0;
        double temp_bias_update = 0;
        for(int input = 0; input < inputs.size(); input++)
        {
            double f = weight * inputs[input] + bias;
            my_calc.push_back(f);
            temp_weight_update += 2*(f - expectedOutputs[input])*inputs[input];
            temp_bias_update += 2*(f - expectedOutputs[input]);
        }
        weight -= learningRate * temp_weight_update / inputs.size();
        bias -= learningRate * temp_bias_update / inputs.size();
        cout << "New weight: " << weight << endl;
        cout << "New bias: " << bias << endl;
        cout << "Loss: " << MSE(my_calc, expectedOutputs) << endl << endl;
    }
}
```

