<h2>II. Linear Regression with Multi-dimensional Inputs and Outputs</h2>

Now we can adjust our model to be able to handle multi-dimensional inputs and outputs. Concretely, this might look like mapping square footage ($x_1$), average income of the zipcode ($x_2$), and city population ($x_3$) to the rent ($y_1$) and average monthly utility bill ($y_2$) for an apartment.

Given we'll be dealing with vectors, we'll go ahead and invoke the help of the <em><a href="http://eigen.tuxfamily.org/index.php?title=Main_Page">Eigen</a></em> library, which contains optimized implementations of vector and matrix objects and operations in C++. Hopefully, this is the only library we'll need to use for a while!

Fortunately, even when we move into higher dimensional spaces, our formulas <em>almost</em> stay the same. However, I will confess that they do get a little more convoluted.

<p align="center">
  <img height="400" width="400" src="https://media.tenor.com/8uZKpgaGe9EAAAAM/hold-onto-your-buts-butt.gif" />
</p>

Given that our weight is now a matrix, $\bold{W}$ (and not a single value), we now have to take the partial derivative with respect to $J$ for every element in $\bold{W}$. Our bias is now also a vector, $\overrightarrow{b}$. With these change, we now have this as the definition of our linear function:

$$
f(\overrightarrow{x}) = \bold{W}\overrightarrow{x} + \overrightarrow{b}
$$

Our cost function also changes a little bit -- we're no longer dealing with 1-D outputs, so our cost function has to reflect that:

$$
MSE =
\frac{1}{nm}
\displaystyle
\sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{j=1}^m(f_j(x^i) - y^i_j)^2
$$
Here, $m$ represents the number of elements in the output vector, and $f_j$ and $y_j$ represent the $j$ components of each respective vector (forgive me if the notation isn't exactly "formal" here). If you think I'm going overboard with summation symbols, get ready for one more as I rewrite MSE in terms of $\bold{W}$ and $\overrightarrow{b}$:
$$
MSE = J(\bold{W}, \overrightarrow{b}) =
\frac{1}{nm}
\displaystyle
\sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{j=1}^m((\sum_{k=1}^t\bold{W}^T_{kj}x^i_k) + b_j - y^i_j)^2
$$

Here, $t$ represents the dimensionality of the input vector ($\overrightarrow{x}$), and $x_k$ represents a component of $\overrightarrow{x}$. $\bold{W}$ has to be transposed in order to allow multiplication between it and the input vector $\overrightarrow{x}$.

Now, just like before, we need the partial derivative of $J$ with respect to each element in $\bold{W}$ and each element in $\overrightarrow{b}$. Things get a little wonky because of the transpose, but just know that although we're calculating the derivative with respect to the transpose for now, we can always "transpose the transpose" and get our original $\bold{W}$ back.:

$$
\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{\bold{W^T_{aj}}}} =
\frac{2}{nm}
\sum_{i=1}^n((\sum_{k=1}^t\bold{W}^T_{kj}x^i_k) + b_j - yx^i_j)x_a
$$

$$
\frac{\partial{J}}{\partial{b_j}} =
\frac{2}{nm}
\sum_{i=1}^n((\sum_{k=1}^t\bold{W}^T_{kj}xx^i_k) + b_j - yx^i_j)
$$

These partial derivatives aren't quite as trivial as the last two, so feel free to bring out the paper and pencil if you're following along. Sadly, given that we've moved into multi-dimensional space, visualizing what is going on here is a little tough, so I can only leave you with the source code for our new MSE function and our new train function.

```js
//* NeuralNet.cpp *//

double NeuralNet::MSE_MULTIDIMENSIONAL(vector<Eigen::VectorXd> &experimental, vector<Eigen::VectorXd> &expected)
{
    double sum = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < experimental.size(); i++)
    {  
        for(int j = 0; j < experimental[i].size(); j++)
        {
            // fix this
            sum += (experimental[i](j) - expected[i](j)) * (experimental[i](j) - expected[i](j)) ;
        }
    }
    return sum / (double)experimental.size();

}

void NeuralNet::eigenTrain(vector<Eigen::VectorXd> &inputs, vector<Eigen::VectorXd> &expected_outputs, int epochs) {
    if (inputs.size() != expected_outputs.size())
    {
        throw runtime_error("must have same number of inputs as outputs");
    }
    if (inputs.size() == 0 || expected_outputs.size() == 0)
    {
        throw runtime_error("must use non-empty inputs and outputs");
    }
    int input_dim = inputs[0].size();
    int output_dim = expected_outputs[0].size();
    Eigen::MatrixXd weights = Eigen::MatrixXd::Random(input_dim, output_dim);
    Eigen::VectorXd biases = Eigen::VectorXd::Random(output_dim);
    for(int epoch = 0; epoch < epochs; epoch++)
    {
        Eigen::MatrixXd temp_weight_updates = Eigen::MatrixXd::Zero(input_dim, output_dim);
        Eigen::VectorXd temp_bias_updates = Eigen::VectorXd::Zero(output_dim);

        vector<Eigen::VectorXd> error_helper;
        for(int input = 0; input < inputs.size(); input++)
        {
            Eigen::VectorXd network_output = weights.transpose() * inputs[input] + biases;
            error_helper.push_back(network_output);
            // part of MSE:
            for(int j = 0; j < network_output.size(); j++)
            {
                for(int k = 0; k < weights.rows(); k++)
                {
                    temp_weight_updates(k, j) += 2 * (network_output(j) - expected_outputs[input](j)) * inputs[input](k);
                }
                temp_bias_updates(j) += 2 * (network_output(j) - expected_outputs[input](j));
            }
        }

        //update step
        weights -= learningRate * temp_weight_updates / (inputs.size() * output_dim);
        biases -= learningRate * temp_bias_updates / (inputs.size() * output_dim);
        cout << "New weight: " << endl << weights << endl;
        cout << "New bias: " << endl << biases << endl;
        cout << "Loss: " << MSE_MULTIDIMENSIONAL(error_helper, expected_outputs) << endl << endl;
    }
}
```

